1
00:00:00,280 --> 00:00:05,200
Do you have yesterday's high and low marked
on your charts right now?

2
00:00:05,200 --> 00:00:07,330
Chances are, you don’t!

3
00:00:07,330 --> 00:00:12,710
Well let me tell you, those previous day levels
are absolutely crucial to be paying attention

4
00:00:12,710 --> 00:00:13,710
to.

5
00:00:13,710 --> 00:00:18,789
One of the most important factors that influence
price action is the previous day's high and

6
00:00:18,789 --> 00:00:20,250
low.

7
00:00:20,250 --> 00:00:25,790
These two levels serve as crucial reference
points, providing valuable insights into the

8
00:00:25,790 --> 00:00:28,800
current market sentiment.

9
00:00:28,800 --> 00:00:33,950
Whenever I look at the price action, one of
the first things I do is plot the highs and

10
00:00:33,950 --> 00:00:35,950
lows of the previous day.

11
00:00:35,950 --> 00:00:38,300
I use this indicator.

12
00:00:38,300 --> 00:00:44,550
Time and again I'll see price testing that
resistance from last session before getting

13
00:00:44,550 --> 00:00:45,620
rejected.

14
00:00:45,620 --> 00:00:49,390
Or finding support right at the lows and bouncing.

15
00:00:49,390 --> 00:00:55,370
Add them to your charts, and just see for
yourself how often the market respects them.

16
00:00:55,370 --> 00:01:01,070
These levels will give you an edge in spotting
reversals and momentum shifts.

17
00:01:01,070 --> 00:01:06,360
And in combination with the VWAP, the high
and low prices from the day before will offer

18
00:01:06,360 --> 00:01:13,270
amazing low-risk/high-reward trade points
neglected by so many traders.

19
00:01:13,270 --> 00:01:16,220
So Why are Previous Day High and Low Important?

20
00:01:16,220 --> 00:01:19,020
Well, there are several reasons:
1.

21
00:01:19,020 --> 00:01:25,030
First, they represent market memory: These
levels represent the maximum and minimum prices

22
00:01:25,030 --> 00:01:28,710
reached by the market in the previous trading
session.

23
00:01:28,710 --> 00:01:34,530
This information captures the collective sentiment
of traders on that particular day, providing

24
00:01:34,530 --> 00:01:37,659
great insights into the market's current direction.

25
00:01:37,659 --> 00:01:38,659
2.

26
00:01:38,659 --> 00:01:44,530
These levels are also liquidity magnets: They
often attract a high volume of buying or selling

27
00:01:44,530 --> 00:01:50,460
orders, as traders anticipate price movements
around these key points.

28
00:01:50,460 --> 00:01:56,140
This increased liquidity can amplify price
movements, creating both opportunities and

29
00:01:56,140 --> 00:01:58,200
risks for traders.

30
00:01:58,200 --> 00:01:59,200
3.

31
00:01:59,200 --> 00:02:04,759
Previous day high and low can also act as
psychological barriers for traders, influencing

32
00:02:04,759 --> 00:02:06,729
their decision-making.

33
00:02:06,729 --> 00:02:13,150
Many traders may be hesitant to enter trades
outside or inside these levels, adding to

34
00:02:13,150 --> 00:02:17,180
the potential for significant price movements.

35
00:02:17,180 --> 00:02:22,560
So each trading day leaves its mark through
the highs and lows it hits.

36
00:02:22,560 --> 00:02:28,590
And other traders watch these levels closely
as potential battle zones, whether the price

37
00:02:28,590 --> 00:02:34,720
was unable to break through resistance or
found support before falling further.

38
00:02:34,720 --> 00:02:40,870
The memory of a day's action sticks around
in traders' minds even after market close.

39
00:02:40,870 --> 00:02:45,700
That’s’ why these levels carry meaning
based on previous activity.

40
00:02:45,700 --> 00:02:51,730
You know that at that point buyers showed
up there to stop a drop.

41
00:02:51,730 --> 00:02:56,370
And sellers overwhelmed the rally attempts
around this area.

42
00:02:56,370 --> 00:03:01,599
You need to have these levels on your chart,
and be ready to take action if price revisits

43
00:03:01,599 --> 00:03:04,620
that area.

44
00:03:04,620 --> 00:03:10,040
One of the coolest things about using those
previous day levels is how versatile they

45
00:03:10,040 --> 00:03:11,069
are.

46
00:03:11,069 --> 00:03:17,160
It doesn't matter if the market is trending
up, down, or sideways - those highs and lows

47
00:03:17,160 --> 00:03:21,420
from the session before are always providing
clues.

48
00:03:21,420 --> 00:03:28,760
In an uptrend, it's amazing how often that
yesterday's low becomes a rock solid foundation.

49
00:03:28,760 --> 00:03:32,049
Price bounces right back up from it quite
often.

50
00:03:32,049 --> 00:03:36,870
Of course, you’ll often see some liquidity
runs below this level.

51
00:03:36,870 --> 00:03:41,470
Don’t ever expect these levels to be respected
to the pip.

52
00:03:41,470 --> 00:03:47,470
On the contrary, expect liquidity hunts above
or below these levels.

53
00:03:47,470 --> 00:03:53,989
Same thing on the flip side - when we're trending
down, the previous high tends to act like

54
00:03:53,989 --> 00:03:59,730
a magnet, pulling price back down after any
bounce.

55
00:03:59,730 --> 00:04:05,720
But it's not just trends - maybe my favorite
is watching the magic in ranging markets.

56
00:04:05,720 --> 00:04:10,890
You'll see price bouncing between those two
levels like clockwork.

57
00:04:10,890 --> 00:04:17,259
Testing the high as resistance before falling
back to find support at the low.

58
00:04:17,259 --> 00:04:22,750
No matter what kind of action the market is
serving up, those past closing levels make

59
00:04:22,750 --> 00:04:27,780
for reliable areas to find structure.

60
00:04:27,780 --> 00:04:32,970
Scouting for breakouts gets a whole lot easier
when you know the zones the market will likely

61
00:04:32,970 --> 00:04:36,030
run into support or resistance.

62
00:04:36,030 --> 00:04:41,910
But maybe even better, you can find reliable
reversal plays even when things are moving

63
00:04:41,910 --> 00:04:42,910
sideways!

64
00:04:42,910 --> 00:04:48,030
The key is stacking the odds in your favor
as much as possible.

65
00:04:48,030 --> 00:04:52,860
For me, that means looking for confluences
on my charts.

66
00:04:52,860 --> 00:04:59,800
If I see price reacting to a day low AND bounce
from a monthly VWAP line, now we're talking

67
00:04:59,800 --> 00:05:02,290
high probability!

68
00:05:02,290 --> 00:05:08,160
That monthly volume-weighted average price
does a great job showing us those dynamic

69
00:05:08,160 --> 00:05:11,000
support and resistance areas.

70
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:16,500
And it's always shifting based on how price
has traded recently.

71
00:05:16,500 --> 00:05:22,520
So keeping tabs on how the market interacts
with those VWAP bands is a great way to spot

72
00:05:22,520 --> 00:05:25,220
reversals in the making.

73
00:05:25,220 --> 00:05:30,690
From studying the market over so many years,
I've noticed some repeatable things about

74
00:05:30,690 --> 00:05:34,330
how price interacts with VWAP bands.

75
00:05:34,330 --> 00:05:41,440
In more rangy conditions when there's no obvious
trend pushing' up or down, I've seen time

76
00:05:41,440 --> 00:05:48,900
and again how reliable it is for price to
bounce between that upper and lower band like

77
00:05:48,900 --> 00:05:50,500
a pinball.

78
00:05:50,500 --> 00:05:56,350
Just pinging' off support at the lower line
before stalling against resistance at the

79
00:05:56,350 --> 00:05:58,220
upper bands.

80
00:05:58,220 --> 00:06:05,660
That middle main VWAP line acts as a real
magnet whether pulling price back up or guiding

81
00:06:05,660 --> 00:06:06,840
it down again.

82
00:06:06,840 --> 00:06:10,210
And it also works a charm in trends.

83
00:06:10,210 --> 00:06:15,480
You’ll often spot price sidling along, respecting
the middle VWAP.

84
00:06:15,480 --> 00:06:22,210
So combining the previous day levels with
VWAP - here’s how theory plays out in real

85
00:06:22,210 --> 00:06:23,810
price action.

86
00:06:23,810 --> 00:06:30,360
The way I see it, when those areas overlap,
that's your high probability trade area right

87
00:06:30,360 --> 00:06:31,360
there.

88
00:06:31,360 --> 00:06:37,919
Think about it - if price is bouncing around
a day's low AND finding' support at a VWAP

89
00:06:37,919 --> 00:06:38,919
band?

90
00:06:38,919 --> 00:06:43,770
You got yourself a perfect confluence zone
to be snapping up some trades.

91
00:06:43,770 --> 00:06:46,470
Great odds the move will reverse in your favor.

92
00:06:46,470 --> 00:06:54,060
Same goes for resistance - when the market
tests yesterday's high but then stalls right

93
00:06:54,060 --> 00:06:55,629
at a VWAP line.

94
00:06:55,629 --> 00:06:58,280
Textbook shorting opportunity.

95
00:06:58,280 --> 00:07:03,580
So always be scouting your charts for where
those levels coincide.

96
00:07:03,580 --> 00:07:10,500
You can see this market was in a bit of an
uptrend based on those higher highs and higher

97
00:07:10,500 --> 00:07:11,700
lows.

98
00:07:11,700 --> 00:07:17,220
But also clearly trading' sideways between
these established zones.

99
00:07:17,220 --> 00:07:23,360
So when price comes down and tests right at
that previous day low AND bounces off the

100
00:07:23,360 --> 00:07:27,970
lower VWAP band, to me that’s strong "buy"!

101
00:07:27,970 --> 00:07:32,599
We got two major support levels stacking the
odds in our favor.

102
00:07:32,599 --> 00:07:34,419
And, there's more!

103
00:07:34,419 --> 00:07:40,050
We had this zone that had previously been
acting as resistance, so doubly consolidating

104
00:07:40,050 --> 00:07:41,370
as support.

105
00:07:41,370 --> 00:07:48,080
Three major forces stacking up under the market
– it doesn't get much better than that!

106
00:07:48,080 --> 00:07:51,590
The entry is near that confluence area.

107
00:07:51,590 --> 00:07:57,660
And a protective stop loss right below it
to mitigate against any potential whipsaws.

108
00:07:57,660 --> 00:08:00,340
Here’s a short set up!

109
00:08:00,340 --> 00:08:06,729
First aspect is we're in a clear sideways
trading zone with no momentum.

110
00:08:06,729 --> 00:08:14,180
Then we've marked our key resistance area
between the previous high and upper VWAP band.

111
00:08:14,180 --> 00:08:19,190
Perfect area to short as soon as we got that
touch of the confluence.

112
00:08:19,190 --> 00:08:20,970
This is the aggressive entry.

113
00:08:20,970 --> 00:08:25,639
As soon as price reaches the zone, you enter
a sell trade.

114
00:08:25,639 --> 00:08:30,991
But for those that are more conservative,
you wait for some sort of confirmation, so

115
00:08:30,991 --> 00:08:37,050
waiting for a red candle bearish rejection
is equally valid.

116
00:08:37,050 --> 00:08:42,810
I'm looking at a stock that has been trading
sideways for the past few days, bouncing between

117
00:08:42,810 --> 00:08:46,399
the high and low from the previous day.

118
00:08:46,399 --> 00:08:51,830
Yesterday, it tested the low several times
but bounced each time.

119
00:08:51,830 --> 00:08:55,660
This tells me that level is providing support.

120
00:08:55,660 --> 00:09:01,779
Today, I see the price dipping again and getting
close to the previous day's low.

121
00:09:01,779 --> 00:09:07,430
But this time, it's also lining up right at
the lower VWAP band.

122
00:09:07,430 --> 00:09:13,000
I know from past performance that this stock
likes to find support at the low.

123
00:09:13,000 --> 00:09:19,820
Adding in the fact it's now reaching both
the low and converging on the lower VWAP,

124
00:09:19,820 --> 00:09:23,220
it sets up a lower risk entry point.

125
00:09:23,220 --> 00:09:30,210
If I enter long as it's testing this confluence
zone, I can set my stop loss just below the

126
00:09:30,210 --> 00:09:31,390
VWAP area.

127
00:09:31,390 --> 00:09:38,459
This gives the trade room to bounce without
risk of triggering the stop on small volatility.

128
00:09:38,459 --> 00:09:46,170
This market had been trending lower over the
past week, with each successive day's low

129
00:09:46,170 --> 00:09:49,440
providing a lower low in the downtrend.

130
00:09:49,440 --> 00:09:54,940
And here, we saw a price drop which closed
near the low of its range.

131
00:09:54,940 --> 00:09:57,829
This established a strong support point.

132
00:09:57,829 --> 00:10:05,579
The next day, price spiked up but then rolled
over at a resistance level from the prior

133
00:10:05,579 --> 00:10:07,200
day's high.

134
00:10:07,200 --> 00:10:13,959
It began descending back down from the upper
VWAP band, showing sellers were active on

135
00:10:13,959 --> 00:10:16,040
those rally attempts.

136
00:10:16,040 --> 00:10:22,180
So when it reached the confluence point of
the previous day's high along with the upper

137
00:10:22,180 --> 00:10:26,279
VWAP band, that was the moment to initiate
the short trade.

138
00:10:26,279 --> 00:10:31,959
Knowing we are still in a firm downtrend,
this setup gave a low-risk entry, with a protective

139
00:10:31,959 --> 00:10:36,610
stop placed above both the resistance levels.

140
00:10:36,610 --> 00:10:38,050
I'm looking at Tesla (TSLA).

141
00:10:38,050 --> 00:10:44,350
The stock has been trending down for the past
week, with lower highs and lower lows.

142
00:10:44,350 --> 00:10:51,740
On the previous day's, there is clear resistance
formed right here, with price testing it twice

143
00:10:51,740 --> 00:10:54,030
but rejecting both times.

144
00:10:54,030 --> 00:10:57,660
.
Today, I notice the price is rallying in the

145
00:10:57,660 --> 00:11:05,270
morning and approaching once again this resistance
level from the prior day, as well as the upper

146
00:11:05,270 --> 00:11:06,790
VWAP band.

147
00:11:06,790 --> 00:11:13,070
This confluence of resistance signals to me
that there is a high probability of a reversal

148
00:11:13,070 --> 00:11:15,320
lower if it reaches this zone.

149
00:11:15,320 --> 00:11:24,620
So, the play here is a short position with
a stop loss placed above the lower VWAP band.

150
00:11:24,620 --> 00:11:30,769
In this example, I see the market has bounced
between the previous high and low, forming

151
00:11:30,769 --> 00:11:32,750
a sideways range.

152
00:11:32,750 --> 00:11:39,920
Then price pushes up to retest the high, but
stalls directly at the upper VWAP band.

153
00:11:39,920 --> 00:11:45,959
This confluence of resistance made for a great
short, since both levels were likely to cause

154
00:11:45,959 --> 00:11:48,819
a reversal.

155
00:11:48,819 --> 00:11:55,480
Here we have an uptrend, and I notice price
is hugging the middle VWAP line nicely.

156
00:11:55,480 --> 00:12:03,010
Then it dips to retest the previous low and
bounces perfectly off the lower VWAP band.

157
00:12:03,010 --> 00:12:10,680
This signal at those stacked supports provided
another low-risk long entry.

158
00:12:10,680 --> 00:12:17,300
Now we have down trending conditions, price
was respecting the VWAP very well.

159
00:12:17,300 --> 00:12:24,061
So when it bumped up to tag yesterday's high,
but rolled over at the upper VWAP band, it

160
00:12:24,061 --> 00:12:28,840
was an ideal short setup with converging resistance.

161
00:12:28,840 --> 00:12:36,610
Again, the market started to range between
the high and low, so I watched for opportunities

162
00:12:36,610 --> 00:12:41,290
when it hit those levels in conjunction with
the VWAP.

163
00:12:41,290 --> 00:12:50,320
A retest of the low coinciding with this VWAP
gave a low-risk entry for the next bounce.

164
00:12:50,320 --> 00:12:57,490
As the trend resumed down, I see another great
short after price failed at the high and turned

165
00:12:57,490 --> 00:12:59,779
off the upper VWAP.

166
00:12:59,779 --> 00:13:06,510
Seeing it reverse at that confluence resistance
area led to another price fade.

167
00:13:06,510 --> 00:13:09,790
I hope you see the potential of this trading,
strategy.

168
00:13:09,790 --> 00:13:13,050
It’s not perfect by any means.

169
00:13:13,050 --> 00:13:19,180
Of course you can refine your entries even
more, using volume or even some smart money

170
00:13:19,180 --> 00:13:20,180
concepts.

171
00:13:20,180 --> 00:13:26,340
So drop a like if you want a follow up video,
and in the meantime you can watch these videos.

